Bank Churn Prediction Project - Warren V. Camp¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Context:¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle.The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId,CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance etc.

Points Distribution:¶

  1. Read the dataset
  2. Drop the columns which are unique for all users like IDs (5 points)
  3. Distinguish the featuresand target variable(5 points)
  4. Divide the data set into training and test sets (5 points)
  5. Normalize the train and test data (10 points)
  6. Initialize & build the model. Identify the points of improvement and implement the same.(20 points)
  7. Predict the results using 0.5 as a threshold (10 points)
  8. Print the Accuracy score and confusion matrix (5 points)

6. Initialize & build the model. Identify the points of improvement and implement the same. (20 points)¶

In [78]:
output_size = 1
validation_split = 0.2 
epochs = 200
lr = 0.0001

# Initialize the constructor
model = tf.keras.models.Sequential()

# Add an input layer with 11 nodes
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(units = 16,activation='relu' ,input_dim = 11, name='dense_layer_1'))

# Add hidden layer
model.add(Dense(units = 16 ,activation='relu', name='dense_layer_2'))

     
# Add an output layer with one node
model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(units = 1, activation = 'sigmoid', name='dense_layer_output'))
In [79]:
OPTIMIZER = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=lr)
 
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer=OPTIMIZER , metrics = ['accuracy'])
In [80]:
%%time

history = model.fit(X_train, y_train ,validation_split=validation_split, batch_size=64,epochs=epochs, verbose=0)

test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(X_test, y_test)
print ('Loss: ', test_loss, 'Accuracy: ', test_acc)

Part A Summary¶

The model was run with different number of learning rates (.0001,.001. .01, .1), epochs(50, 100, 200,300), hidden layers (1, 2), and nodes (8, 10, 13, 21, 34, 52, 111), activation(relu, tanh, sigmoid), and optimizer (Adam, SGD) . Accuracy ranged from .8415 to .865. My objective was to achieve minimum loss, good accuracy at .9 or higher and good Confusion Matrix results. The sample run listed above has a Loss score of 0.3595 and an Accuracy score of 0.8530. However, the purpose of this model is to identify potential churn customers and determine how to keep them as bank customers. The Confusion Matrix (224 wrong and 187 correct) indicates (recall is only .45 and f1 is .56) that the model is no better than flipping a coin for determining if a customer is likely churn candidate. The data or lack of data for previous churn customers is only 20% of our population. To improve the model, we need to address the data imbalance. This will be shown in Part C. Information that may be valuable to management includes most customers are from France (50%), are male (55%), average credit score is 650 with a range from 850 to 350. Other statistical information is listed above.

Part B Summary¶

Part B was an attempt to improve performance by feature/dimension reduction. Three features were selected for removal (EstimatedSalary, Geography_France, and Geography_Germany). The model did make a small improvement in performance over the first model. The Loss score is 0.3565 and the accuracy score is 0.8595. Churn recall and f1 dropped down to 0.,49 and 0.59. Again, this was a small improvement in performance.

May be another approach to consider is combining the three dropped features creating a new feature to be included in the model or better tuning the hyperparameters.

Part C Summary¶

Part C attempted to improve model performance by addressing the imbalance with the target dated (Exited). The SMOTE function increased the number of records related to churned customers. As a result, for the 411 records in the test file, 312 were corrected identified and 99 were incorrectly identified. This was an improvement from 50% probability to 80% probability. However, while Recall improved from .45 to ..76, the f1 score decrease from .56 to .45 and accuracy changed from .85 to .62. While increasing the number of churned records helped, more work needs to do to improve the accuracy and minimize loss function. The decrease in the f1 and accuracy scores can be attributed to greatly increased number of false positives from 82 to 659.
